In[21]:
key = "_pleasant_weather"
stations = []
figure, ax = plt.subplots(3, 5, figsize=(25,15))
figure.suptitle('Decision Tress Unscaled Confusion Matrix - Train set', fontsize=16)

labels = ['pleasant', 'unpleasant']   
count=0
for i in range(3):
    for j in range(5):
        name = locations_A1[count]
        cm = confusion_matrix(y_train.loc[:,name+key], y_pred_train[:,count])
        disp = ConfusionMatrixDisplay(confusion_matrix=cm)
        ax[i,j] = sns.heatmap(cm, annot=True, fmt='g', ax=ax[i,j]);
        # labels, title and ticks
        ax[i,j].set_xlabel('Predicted labels');
        ax[i,j].set_ylabel('True labels'); 
        ax[i,j].set_title(name +' Matrix'); 
        count+=1

plt.savefig('DT_train_confusion_matrix_unscaled.png', bbox_inches='tight')
plt.show()

Do you think the decision tree needs to be pruned? Why?

I've tested this decision tree model convergence matrix several times.
I've gotten different results each time, but the accuracy is around 0.6.
It's clear that this model doesn't predict the outcome very well,
and I think it has something to do with the shape of the decision tree being too complex.
But I'm not sure if I should prune this model or not.

        name = locations_A1[count]

        ax[i,j] = sns.heatmap(cm, annot=True, fmt='g', ax=ax[i,j]);
        # labels, title and ticks
        ax[i,j].set_xlabel('Predicted labels');
        ax[i,j].set_ylabel('True labels'); 
        ax[i,j].set_title(name +' Matrix');

#Create the ANN
#hidden_layer_sizes has up to three layers, each with a number of nodes. So (5, 5) is two hidden layers with 5 nodes each,
#and (100, 50, 25) is three hidden layers with 100, 50, and 25 nodes.
mlp = MLPClassifier(hidden_layer_sizes=(5, 5), max_iter=500, tol=0.0001)
#Fit the data to the model
mlp.fit(X_train_sc, y_train_sc)

Which of these algorithms (including the KNN model from Exercise 1.4) do you think best predicts the current data?

Since the ANNs model was the most accurate, I believe it is the best fit for this data.

Are any weather stations fully accurate? Is there any overfitting happening?

However, for the ANNs model, when I significantly increased the hidden layers, it was more accurate on the training set, but barely improved on the test set, so I suspect it was overfitted for the training set to some extent.

Are there certain features of the data set that might contribute to the overall accuracy?

I don't know much about this.

Which model would you recommend that ClimateWins use?

If you want to tune the layers of the ANNs model to improve the accuracy on the test set, I would recommend using the ANNs model.
